    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The goblin thing? Oh, you know, just a little bit of flavor! It’s just that when you're talking about contracts and money, it reminds me of how greedy and unpredictable those little creatures are. You've got to keep a watchful eye on things, just like you would a hoard of misplaced shiny things!\n\nNow, about the foundation issues and the escrow money—this is where the contract really matters, and it's far more complex than just a single, simple goblin raid. The escrow account itself doesn't *control* the money in the sense that it decides who gets it; it just *holds* it until the contractual conditions are met.\n\nIf the inspection reveals major foundation issues, the buyer usually invokes a contingency clause in the purchase agreement. This clause is the key, not the escrow account itself. The buyer uses this contingency to negotiate repairs, request a price reduction, or, if the issues are too severe, walk away from the deal entirely and get their earnest money back.\n\nThe seller *cannot* just take the earnest money to cover repairs unilaterally. If the buyer walks away due to a failed inspection contingency, the escrow agent will typically return the earnest money to the buyer, because the",
