      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, you've got the right idea—the escrow agent is essentially the neutral middleman, the impartial referee in this whole property squabble. They are the gatekeeper, ensuring that no one grabs the funds before the agreed-upon conditions are met. It's less like a simple middleman and more like a highly cautious, contract-bound custodian, which is a lot more responsible than a typical goblin merchant!\n\nIf a dispute arises over the foundation—say, the buyer wants a $20,000 credit for repairs, but the seller insists it’s fine—and you both can't agree, the money doesn't just sit there forever like a forgotten pile of rusty trinkets. If the parties truly deadlock, the escrow agent will usually advise both sides to escalate the dispute. This often means involving mediation or arbitration, which are structured ways to resolve the disagreement outside of a full-blown court battle.\n\nIn the worst-case scenario, if mediation fails, the dispute can end up in litigation. At that point, a judge steps in, and *the judge* directs the escrow agent on how to release the funds—to the buyer, to the seller, or perhaps to cover specific agreed-",
